# Assignment 5 – User-Level Threads + Mutex: Results

## Context-Switching Approach

Threads are switched using `uswtch(struct context **old, struct context *new)`
implemented in `uswtch.S`. The routine:

1. Saves the current thread's callee-saved registers (`ebp`, `ebx`, `esi`, `edi`)
   and stack pointer into `*old`.
2. Loads `new` as the stack pointer.
3. Pops the saved registers of the incoming thread and returns into it.

The return address at the top of each thread's saved context frame determines
where execution resumes: for a brand-new thread this is `thread_stub`, which
calls the user function and then marks the thread ZOMBIE before yielding.

The scheduler (`thread_yield`) is purely cooperative: a thread must call
`thread_yield()` to give up the CPU. The scheduler uses round-robin selection
over all RUNNABLE threads.

## Mutex Implementation

`umutex_t` contains a single `int locked` field. Because scheduling is
cooperative, only one thread runs at a time, making the check-and-set sequence
in `mutex_lock` safe without hardware atomics:

```
while(m->locked) thread_yield();
m->locked = 1;
```

A thread that finds the lock held yields immediately, avoiding busy-waiting
from a single thread monopolizing the CPU.

## Test: Producer-Consumer (`test_pc`)

Two producer threads each insert 200 items into an 8-slot circular buffer;
one consumer thread removes all 400 items. The mutex protects all accesses to
`buf`, `head`, `tail`, and `count`. Threads yield when the buffer is full
(producers) or empty (consumer), allowing cooperative progress.

Expected output (every 100 items consumed):
```
consumer got 100 items (last=...)
consumer got 200 items (last=...)
consumer got 300 items (last=...)
consumer got 400 items (last=...)
test_pc: done
```

## Limitations

| Property | Value |
|---|---|
| Maximum threads | 16 (including main) |
| Stack size per thread | 4096 bytes |
| Scheduling policy | Cooperative round-robin |
| Atomic ops required | None (cooperative guarantees safety) |
| Kernel modifications | None |

Deeply recursive thread functions may overflow the 4096-byte stack. This can
be raised by increasing `STACK_SIZE` in `uthread.c`.